    "body": "## Description:\r\n\r\nThis pull request introduces a universal loader for system-wide Tree-sitter parsers in Neovim, featuring automatic filetype mapping and an ABI compatibility check with detailed warnings sent to :messages.\r\n\r\n\r\n## User story:\r\nMaria installs Neovim from her Linux distribution’s system package. To write her first screenplay, she also installs the `tree-sitter-fountain` package (for more information on the Fountain filetype, see https://fountain.io). She’s ready to start writing—no Lua plugins for .fountain documents required for this example.\r\n\r\nMaria doesn’t have a C compiler installed, nor does she know what one is, and she doesn’t want to be bothered with it. Her future fame in The West End awaits!\r\n\r\n## Background:\r\n\r\nThis pull request proposes a mechanism enabling Neovim to automatically recognise and use system-wide pre-compiled Tree-sitter modules. For reference, see the list of available modules in the openSUSE Tree-sitter project (note, paradoxically tree-sitter-fountain isn’t yet packaged, although it exists on https://github.com/gboere/tree-sitter-fountain).\r\n\r\nIn openSUSE/Factory, these packages are installed universally for all consumers (including Neovim, Helix, and Emacs right now) in `/usr/lib64/tree_sitter/*.so`. This directory is symlinked to `/usr/share/nvim/runtime/parser`, meaning even built-in parsers for languages like C, Markdown, and Lua are provided by system-wide packages.\r\n\r\nHowever, this setup doesn’t currently work out-of-the-box with Neovim, as it doesn’t automatically recognize new parsers in the `parser/` directory. This Lua module resolves that issue by enabling automatic parser recognition.",
