        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "> The parsers built by Neovim are the same parsers built in the openSUSE packaging.\r\n\r\nThen this PR isn't needed since the build scripts take care of everything already.\r\n\r\n> There isn't any interference into the prebuilds shipped by Neovim, this is about distribution packaging of tree-sitter parser as already done by other distributions.\r\n\r\nIf you change the installed `runtime` directory, you are interfering.\r\n\r\n> Source to that? If tree-sitter is that unstable who is it even suitable for production use?\r\n\r\nSource: Personal knowledge as maintainer of Neovim, tree-sitter, nvim-treesitter, and the treesitter-grammars project.\r\n\r\nAnd it's not unstable if you use it exactly as intended. \r\n\r\n(This is off-topic but: tree-sitter is originally designed as a monolithic full-stack component _including parsers_, e.g., for Github's `linguist` syntax highlighting module. Neovim's distributed \"plugin model\" is very much not envisioned, and I've been fighting against the resulting friction for years.)",
