        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "To be clear, you can already use whatever parser you want, as long as it is called `<lang>.so` and placed in a `parser` directory anywhere on runtimepath (and same with the queries). _And this needs to be done intentionally by the user_. Anything beyond that -- especially targeting a single distribution -- is completely out of scope.\r\n\r\nSo the reason I closed this PR is that it is just a hacky reimplementation of functionality _we already have_ for a hardcoded non-standard directory.\r\n\r\nAnd this: \r\n\r\n> However, this setup doesn’t currently work out-of-the-box with Neovim, as it doesn’t automatically recognize new parsers in the parser/ directory. \r\n\r\nis simply false. (If it's not working _for you_, there's an issue with your config or installation. Try `:checkhealth vim.treesitter`.)\r\n",
